`crates/steno/tests` is the integration-test surface for the `steno` crate: it validates the public parse→expand→render/emit pipeline (`parse_source`, `parse_template`, `expand_counts`/`expand_dict`, `expand_types_one`, `render_plain`/`render_smart`/`render_snippet`/`emit_struct`, and the stroke API) end-to-end, plus a checked-in Neovim plugin and a C++ differential harness. Depending on this crate means these tests are the executable spec of chunk grammar, stroke canonicalization, count/type expansion arithmetic, and rendered output syntax (indent width, auto-close set, movement-event encoding).

The dominant coupling: most files (`blocks`, `expand`, `expand_types`, `infinite`, `landing_reuse`, `parse_source`, `render`, `smart`, `snippet`, `stroke_order`) load the real `dict.steno` (or `dict.infinite.steno`) from the repo root via a `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`-relative path, and hardcode specific strokes, counts, and corpus-size thresholds (>70 entries, >1000 dict keys, "14 minus 4 @noarg", etc.). Editing `dict.steno` — renaming/removing a stroke, changing a count/arity, adding an `@noarg` type — can silently break tests across many of these files simultaneously; there is no single owner of corpus compatibility. `smart.rs` and `snippet.rs` additionally hand-construct a synthetic `TypedEntry`/`Entry` (`template_literal`/`terminal_entry`) to preserve coverage the corpus stopped providing after `STKWR-LT` was repurposed — anyone changing `Entry`/`TypedEntry`'s field set must update both synthesized paths together.

`cpp_check.rs` and `infinite.rs` pin the walker/Pass-A pipeline against two independent oracles (a C++ reference implementation and `expand_dict` on an enumerable subset); both assume `build_tables`/`parse_source`/emit stay in lockstep with `build-javelin`. `nvim_plugin.rs` is the only file exercising the Lua runtime rather than Rust internals, and depends on sentinel constants (`SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE`) also referenced in `snippet.rs`'s assertions — changing those strings requires updating both. `editor.rs` and `blocks.rs` together pin the auto-indent/editor-simulation contract (`interpret`, `Behaviors` presets) that `emit_struct`'s output is checked against.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory.